docs/product-specs/oauth-consent-and-token-runtime.md:4:The mock OAuth server issues JWT bearer tokens through browser consent and client credentials, with endpoint-level permissions and revocation.
docs/product-specs/oauth-consent-and-token-runtime.md:16:- OAuth clients store redirect URIs, client credentials TTL presets, and a maximum allowed endpoint set that later consent and client credentials flows must not exceed
docs/product-specs/oauth-consent-and-token-runtime.md:20:- consent displays client, redirect URI, resource, user, authorization-code TTL, and an endpoint permission checklist constrained to the client's allowed endpoint set
docs/product-specs/oauth-consent-and-token-runtime.md:21:- approving consent creates a single-use-ready authorization code bound to client, redirect URI, user, selected endpoints, resource/audience, state, expiry, and unused status, then redirects with `code` and `state`
docs/product-specs/oauth-consent-and-token-runtime.md:23:- `/oauth/token` supports the `authorization_code` grant with form-encoded `grant_type`, `code`, `redirect_uri`, `client_id`, and `client_secret`
docs/product-specs/oauth-consent-and-token-runtime.md:24:- valid code exchange marks the code used, returns `access_token`, `token_type`, `expires_in`, and `scope`, and stores issued token metadata by JWT `jti`
docs/product-specs/oauth-consent-and-token-runtime.md:25:- access tokens are RS256 JWTs with issuer, audience/resource, subject, client ID, grant type, issued/expiry times, `jti`, scope, and `endpoint_permissions`
docs/product-specs/oauth-consent-and-token-runtime.md:34:- Non-built-in OAuth client CRUD validates client ID shape, redirect URI shape, TTL presets, unique client IDs, and existing allowed endpoint IDs
docs/product-specs/oauth-consent-and-token-runtime.md:37:- Consent endpoint selection must be a subset of the registered OAuth client's allowed endpoint IDs
